  "46": {
    "John Trapp": "Blind Bartimeus ] Named and celebrated in the Gospel, when many mighty monarchs are utterly forgotten, or else lie shrouded in the sheet of shame.\n46. Blind Bartimeus] Named and celebrated in the Gospel, when many mighty monarchs are utterly forgotten, or else lie shrouded in the sheet of shame.",
    "R. Alan Culpepper": "reports all of these actions as though he\nacted alone. [Joseph of Arimathea in Later Legends]\nThe report that Mary Magdalene and Mary `[char_Mary_Ref]`\nthe mother of Joses [The Lists of Women in Mark] saw\nwhere Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` buried Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` serves as a transition\nto the discovery of the empty tomb in the next\nparagraph. Their presence at Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 burial is\nimportant because it ensures that the women\ndid not mistakenly go to the wrong tomb.\nMoreover, the fact that Mark does not say that\nthe women assisted Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` in the burial, as they\npresumably would have if he had been a disciple, supports the conclu-\nsion that they did not know him and that he was a member of the\nSanhedrin fulfilling the duty to bury the dead.86\nCONNECTIONS\n[v_Mrk_15_1] [v_Mrk_15_2] [v_Mrk_15_3] [v_Mrk_15_4] [v_Mrk_15_5] [v_Mrk_15_6] [v_Mrk_15_7] [v_Mrk_15_8] [v_Mrk_15_9] [v_Mrk_15_10] [v_Mrk_15_11] [v_Mrk_15_12] [v_Mrk_15_13] [v_Mrk_15_14] [v_Mrk_15_15] Mark 15:1-15\nThe vividness of Mark\u2019s description of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 trial before Pilate and the\nirony of the release of Barabbas and the condemnation of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` have\nimprinted this scene on the memories and imaginations of Christians\nthrough the centuries. Mel Gibson\u2019s film The Passion of the Christ char-\nacterizes the chief priests as stern and inflexible while Pilate is much\nmore human. In doing so, the film follows the tendency to blame the\nJewish leaders for Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 death while exonerating Roman authority that\ncan be traced back to the time of the writing of the Gospels. The Jewish\nreligious leaders probably were more concerned about Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 activities\nthan Pilate was, but Christian tradition has all too often seized upon\n571\n[v_Mrk_15_1] [v_Mrk_15_2] [v_Mrk_15_3] [v_Mrk_15_4] [v_Mrk_15_5] [v_Mrk_15_6] [v_Mrk_15_7] [v_Mrk_15_8] [v_Mrk_15_9] [v_Mrk_15_10] [v_Mrk_15_11] [v_Mrk_15_12] [v_Mrk_15_13] [v_Mrk_15_14] [v_Mrk_15_15] [v_Mrk_15_16] [v_Mrk_15_17] [v_Mrk_15_18] [v_Mrk_15_19] [v_Mrk_15_20] [v_Mrk_15_21] [v_Mrk_15_22] [v_Mrk_15_23] [v_Mrk_15_24] [v_Mrk_15_25] [v_Mrk_15_26] [v_Mrk_15_27] [v_Mrk_15_28] [v_Mrk_15_29] [v_Mrk_15_30] [v_Mrk_15_31] [v_Mrk_15_32] [v_Mrk_15_33] [v_Mrk_15_34] [v_Mrk_15_35] [v_Mrk_15_36] [v_Mrk_15_37] [v_Mrk_15_38] [v_Mrk_15_39] [v_Mrk_15_40] [v_Mrk_15_41] [v_Mrk_15_42] [v_Mrk_15_43] [v_Mrk_15_44] [v_Mrk_15_45] [v_Mrk_15_46] [v_Mrk_15_47] Mark 15:1-47\nJoseph of Arimathea in Later Legends\nIn the 4th-c. Acts of Pilate the Jewish\nauthorities hold Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` under house\narrest because he provided Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 body a proper\nburial. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` himself appeared to Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, and\nJoseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` reported Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 descent into hell and\nraising of the dead to Annas and Caiaphas. He\nthen led them to Arimathea to see Simeon and\nhis sons, who had been raised from the dead.\nIn the medieval histories of Glastonbury in\nEngland, Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` traveled to England from Gaul,\nwhere he had worked with Philip the Apostle. He\nwas given the island of Glastonbury (or Avalon in\nthe King Arthur legends). There he built a church\nin honor of Mary `[char_Mary_Ref]`. Still later legend reported that\nJoseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` brought the Holy Grail to England. Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`\ntherefore figures in the Arthurian legends, in\nGalahad\u2019s vision of the Holy Grail. Finally, the\nJoseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` legend added that Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` was Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019\nuncle, a merchant, and that he took the boy\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` with him on a journey to England.\nWilhelm Schneemelcher, ed., New Testament Apocrypha\n(trans. R. McL. Wilson; Louisville: Westminster John `[char_John_Ref]` Knox,\n1991), 1:513\u201321; Raymond E. Brown, The Death of the Messiah\n(New York: Doubleday, 1994), 2:1232\u201334; Marie Michelle\nWalsh, \u201cJoseph of Arimathea,\u201d A Dictionary of Biblical Tradition\nin English Literature (ed. David `[char_David_Rut_4]` Lyle Jeffrey; Grand Rapids: Wm.\nB. Eerdmans, 1992), 412.\nthe negative characterization of the chief priests and Pharisees and\nturned it into a justification for anti-Semitism. Mark is not anti-Jewish\nor anti-Semitic. The failure of the religious authorities to recognize\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` as the Messiah is part of Mark\u2019s theme that everyone failed\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2014his hometown, his family, his disciples, and finally even the\nwomen at the cross. None was faithful, yet Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` died for all: \u201cFor the\nSon of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life a"
  },
